hj_b_consier: Human trust in the working subject, potential dangerous manipulation, straightforward for humans
Some tasks (craftsman, construction) are difficult to automatise.
Human empathy seems something AI can’t replaced easily
As far as I understand "full automation of labor" entails "all" work done by humans can be automated, I don't think we are anywhere near that scenario.
AI hype is extremely overblown relative to what the tech is capable of, and reflects a stunted and nihilistic understanding of what a human is.

The current machine learning approaches, including transformer, are still advanced versions of copy and paste. For example, I cannot see whether they can create a new field in math, just like group theory.
it seems to me that less creative tasks, or the tasks that need high robotic advancement would be automated later in the future.

While the progress of ai in the last decade was impressive, current systems lack important common sense, creativity and logical reasoning. I cannot imagine occupations, where these skills are essential to be replaced in this century...or at all.

For labor automation, not only "brains" but also "bodies" are needed in many cases. Development of AI is significant and it is partially super-human, but development of physical robotics is still far behind human capability in most tasks.
Someone must be in control. Most likely scientific community. That cannot be fully automatic.

* I answered Retail salesperson thinking of big chain stores like Target, Walmart, where the retail salesperson mostly tells you where the item you’re looking for is — and this is mainly automatable. Sometimes there are questions that require some logic (eg at Home Depot questions about which tools to buy), and these may take a few more years to automate. But the question seems fundamentally flawed: for retail salesperson jobs at “mom and pop” stores, what customers are looking for is a human connection, and so robots will inherently be unable to automate humans because the job requirement implicitly includes being human. Maybe these “mom and pop” stores will go out of business/style, but the job description as it stands today seems by definition non-automatable.* There have been recent advances in driverless vehicle technology, but the systems are still flawed in their out-of-distribution behavior. Here advances in logical thinking seem like they should precede the driverless technology. I find it feasible that in the next 10 years we will have the necessary advances in AI performing logic to be able to create early prototypes of truck drivers.* There is a human element in surgeon-patient interactions that is not automatable, barring a cultural shift that makes humans not care about this human element. Insofar as the surgery itself, I do not know much about what is involved, but I presume it is: (a) medical knowledge & ability to specialize it to the specific case (which requires some logical thinking), (b) computer vision, (c) robotic manipulation. Of these, it seems (c) is the bottleneck, and I would give it 20 years for 50% chance… although of course I don’t know.* AI researcher will evolve as a job — it involves “research” which is constantly changing by definition! Will machines become as good as or better than humans at reasoning, experimentation, and tuning AI algorthms? It seems that way! Will they become better at setting new directions and asking important new questions? Also it seems like they will! But, provided we live in a human-driven society, we will want humans to understand the AI and what the AI tells us! The role of the AI researcher will not be necessarily to push for better models, but rather to certify the safety of these models and keep them in check and make sure they are aligned with human interests. I don’t see this fundamental job, which has a strong ethical component to it, ever being automated as long as humans are still in control.

For some jobs, AI may be able to do 80-90% of a job. But the remaining 10% is often fuzzy and ill-defined and AI may have a hard time doing that. For others, the roles will be redefined. For example, a surgeon may decide, say what part to cut, and a AI controlled robot may cut that part, but the surgeon will retain the ultimate decision authority.
Moravec's paradox – today's AI is much better at things that are hard for humans eg. scanning thousands of photos – than those that are relatively easy eg. folding laundry
Like after the industrial revolution there will always be new tasks.
Feasibility, current rate of AI progress
